name: Muluken
goals:
Personal Statement
My academic and professional background on water resources together with high water resources potential to my country and the growing demand for policy and management of water resources to use the potential for its development to alleviate the recurrent food security problem is the standing agenda of the country always motivates me to upgrade and update myself attend this course. The rights and obligations of water users, the fundamental principles of water resources management, the institutions in charge of its implementation and enforcement, and the participation of users and their associations in the sustainable development of water. 
In addition to the environmental, public health, hydro power generation, growth of greenery, and other human needs of water (domestic use, sanitation, transportation, tourism, industry, small manufacturing enterprises and services); agricultural intensification, expanding irrigated agriculture, is widely seen as the pathway to our food security problem. Earth's water resources, including rivers, lakes, oceans, and underground aquifers, are under stress in many regions.  Learning how water is distributed around the globe; how it cycles among the oceans, atmosphere, and land; and how human activities are affecting our finite supply of usable water is being very crucial currently.
Water resources policies, laws and management are key tool to help to improve standards of living and alleviate poverty. It will help relevant institutions of the Government of Ethiopia and people throughout the society to understand the benefits of water for daily life and socio-economic development, and to participate in effective, sustainable maintenance, management, conservation, and use of water resources. 
Understanding the substantive international water law principles that ought to be taken into consideration when sharing international water and helps in developing a culture of communication on the principles of utilization the resources upstream and downstream international watercourses. The soft law of the Sustainable Development Goals (SDGs) provides further impetus to the management of transboundary water resources directly through Goal 6.5: implement integrated water resources management at all levels, and through transboundary cooperation as appropriate, and indirectly through Goal 16: promote peaceful and inclusive societies for sustainable development. Thus I have a very high demand for training in the domain of international water law as it enables me to create appropriate legal frameworks for transboundary water cooperation and sustainable water management particularly legal professionals and policy-makers in developing countries and least-developed countries like Ethiopia), where a substantial training gap in the domain of International Water Law found.
I hope the course will provide me advanced knowledge of the principles and norms that govern the use, sharing management and protection of these resources. It will enable me to know more in achieving equitable and sustainable use the resources and share knowledge and experiences with professionals Hence the course will update my academic background (technical and professional) and will increase my knowledge and help me to contribute in the policy making and management of the water sector in my organizations and to my country.  The training will help me in updating my work experiences, qualities, skills and exploring my potential and my country potential so that I can contribute to the sector right after the completion of the course.
